I will start by setting up the database tables for the **Support Ticket System**. I've expanded the schema to include a `ticket_messages` table, which is essential for the chat-like conversation feature you requested.

### Step 1: Database Setup
Please run this in your **Supabase Dashboard -> SQL Editor**:

```sql
-- 1. Support Tickets Table
create table if not exists public.support_tickets (
  id uuid default gen_random_uuid() primary key,
  user_id uuid references auth.users not null,
  category text not null,
  subject text not null,
  status text default 'open' check (status in ('open', 'replied', 'closed')),
  created_at timestamp with time zone default now()
);

-- 2. Ticket Messages (For the conversation)
create table if not exists public.ticket_messages (
  id uuid default gen_random_uuid() primary key,
  ticket_id uuid references public.support_tickets(id) on delete cascade not null,
  sender_id uuid references auth.users not null,
  message text not null,
  attachments jsonb default '[]', -- Array of URLs
  created_at timestamp with time zone default now()
);

-- 3. Update App Settings for Telegram Link
alter table public.app_settings
  add column if not exists telegram_support_link text default 'https://t.me/your_channel';

-- 4. Enable RLS
alter table public.support_tickets enable row level security;
alter table public.ticket_messages enable row level security;

-- 5. Policies for Support Tickets
create policy "Users can view own tickets" on support_tickets for select using (auth.uid() = user_id);
create policy "Users can insert own tickets" on support_tickets for insert with check (auth.uid() = user_id);
create policy "Admins can view all tickets" on support_tickets for select using (public.is_admin());
create policy "Admins can update all tickets" on support_tickets for update using (public.is_admin());

-- 6. Policies for Ticket Messages
create policy "Users can view own ticket messages" on ticket_messages for select 
  using (exists (select 1 from support_tickets where id = ticket_messages.ticket_id and user_id = auth.uid()) OR public.is_admin());
create policy "Everyone authenticated can insert messages" on ticket_messages for insert 
  with check (auth.role() = 'authenticated');

-- 7. Storage Bucket for Support Screenshots
insert into storage.buckets (id, name, public) values ('support', 'support', true) on conflict (id) do nothing;
create policy "Public Support Access" on storage.objects for select using ( bucket_id = 'support' );
create policy "Authenticated Support Upload" on storage.objects for insert with check ( bucket_id = 'support' AND auth.role() = 'authenticated' );
```

I will now create the **Support UI components** and integrate them into the **Account Dashboard**. I've decided to place Support inside the Account page to maintain the professional 5-tab mobile standard, while making it a very prominent "Quick Action."

### Step 2: Create Support Components
I am creating `src/components/SupportSystem.tsx` which will handle the ticket list, creation, and chat view.

